Functions, exit codes, and error handling.

A function lets you give a name to a block of commands and call it like a command of its own. You define it with a name, parentheses, and a body in braces, and then you simply use the name to run it. Inside a function, arguments arrive exactly as they do in a script, as dollar-one, dollar-two, and so on, and they temporarily shadow the script's own arguments while the function runs. There are a couple of definition styles, but the simplest, name followed by empty parentheses and a brace block, is the most portable.

One habit matters a great deal: declare any variable you do not want leaking out with the word local. Without it, every variable a function sets is global to the whole script, which is a fertile source of subtle, baffling bugs. Local keeps a function's working variables contained.

Now, exit codes. Every command returns one: zero for success, non-zero for failure, and different non-zero codes can carry different meanings, documented in the manual pages. You can inspect the previous command's exit code through the special variable dollar-question-mark, and you can set your own script's exit code explicitly with the exit command, by convention using zero for success, one for a generic failure, and two for misuse or bad arguments. There is one important distinction inside functions: use return rather than exit, because exit would terminate the entire script, whereas return just ends the function and hands back a code. A function with no explicit return simply yields the exit code of its last command, which often reads very cleanly, letting you use the function directly as the condition of an if statement.
